<font color="#FF0000">BOURBON AND BRANCHWATER TO GO</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb 15 23:23:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Thank you one and all, via e mail and by posting. Like my memories of the 60's (sex, drugs &amp; rock &amp; roll were GOOD, draft cards and constant worry re: the local draft board and 1A notices were BAD), this site pulls me, talks to me, draws me back.  <br><br>
Perhaps the real issue is not that the Viet Nam War was wrong, not that we should not have been there, not that we were (some of us)protesting, not that protestors broke the law, and not that some protestors spit on vets and some vet's kicked the crap out of some protestors...rather, the sad reality is Viet Nam WON and the USA lost.  This was the first war that the US of A ever 'lost', and that cold fact is the hot coal burning in all of our guts.  Strip away everything else, and that is the cold reality. The fall of Saigon, the helicopter lifting off the embassy roof, 56,000 dead american kids, millions of dead viet's, and for what? Uncle Ho won and the US left with it's tail between its collective legs. A bitter pill for the viewers back home.<br><br>
As a country and a society, the simplistic way was to either blame the soldiers or ignore them.  Forget the rules of no-win, forget that Washington was to blame, what Mr. and Mrs. John Q. Citizen saw was a war lost, and if they were lucky enough to not have their child come home in a body bag, or stoned out of his gizzard, or had become a long haired sex machine, or other less than nice choices, mom and pop america just wanted it all to go away.  Like it never happened.<br><br>
And so now, and here, we all ponder why we still carry anger and guilt, protestor and soldier, when the reason is as simple as the evening news.  No one in America likes a loser, and the veteran was easy to blame.  <br><br>
The hippies are long gone, and so the protestors, but the viet nam vets are still around, usually holding up a sign on the freeway on ramp saying &quot;Will work for food-homeless-Viet Vet-God Bless&quot;. Of course these mentally ill fools are probably not vets, nor homeless, but for Ma and Pa Kettle, they serve as that reminder of a LOSER!!.  Jane Fonda, i.e. Mrs Ted Turner did just find, and still looks good, and ol Tom Hayden now wants to be the Mayor of Los Angeles, so the protestors got the best of the media-public relations image awards when compared to the homeless con artists at the corner.<br><br>
J.J. the Boonirat, you are right. this SHOULD feel like group therapy, IT IS.  <br><br>
Arthur V. You seem to represent a fair and balanced viewpoint.<br><br>
Alex Hernandez. You still keep wanting to brag about being the killer from above. Why is that?  Was killing from above (i.e. a gunship) safe and autonomous, as compared to a ranger with a knife in hand to hand struggle?  Makes me wonder about where you are coming from, but you do represent another spoke in this collective wheel. Let me know when it's your turn in the hotseat, I want to be there.<br><br>
docdel, your searching and thinking shows in your writing, and the depth of your seeking, and caring.<br><br>
Nurse Ratchet, whom ever you really are, I still choose to disagree with you, perhaps you might share something more about who you are in order to validate your opinions??<br><br>
Chet Botkins, on the mark as usual.  <br><br>
I, like JJ, feel like I was out of town and now have returned and this is OUR group therapy weekly session. Only a bit more compressed.  I'm glad to be back. I'm glad to acknowledge you all, right and wrong, as fellow survivors, fellow victims, but best of all, fellows on the same road that will lead to both our own freedom, and to make sure our kids NEVER get tricked down this path like we were.<br><br>
I ask you all to back read as many posts as you can. That is one way to really learn from this site, although my site crashes if I try and go back to far (hint to webmaster - Can you open up the old posts all the way back to # 1 ??) The evolution of our conversations could well be written up and worthy of others attention.<br><br>
Jesus! Did I really get this mellow in just one month away? Must be something in the water.  
